[h1][b](NOT)[/b] Stranger Things: The Game[/h1]

[b]PROS:[/b]
+ Retro charm ;
+ Cryptic story managed to keep me interested throughout the whole playthrough ;
+ Very well paced storytelling. The game continuously gives you the stuff that keeps you going and makes you scratch your head in increments you can digest ;
+ The developers didn't lean on the game being text-driven to excuse themselves from adding some twists on how the experience is presented to the player ;
+ Pretty avant-garde overall.

[b]CONS:[/b]
- Often times a bit on the slow side ;
- No Code lost a tremendous chance to truly break the 4th wall [i]in lieu[/i] of delivering a fully linear storyline (more on this below) ;
- Virtually no replay value - something to be expected but not desired in games like this.

_______________

[b]Stories Untold[/b] is a text-heavy [i]puzzle meets visual novel[/i] game (or something). I was excited to play this game for the premise and went in knowing very little about what the game actually consisted in, as I've been noticing it to be the best way to experience short plot-oriented games. There's a total of 4 episodes to go through, each clocking at approximately 1 hour and providing the player a slightly different experience than the last one. Stories Untold isn't very ornate ; it's in how quirky it looks and feels that you'll find its beauty. But don't be fooled by the labels stuck to this game - although definitely a text-heavy game at times reminiscent of the 80's interactive fiction games, there's a lot more to look at than just text. That is, in fact, where this game managed to impress me the most: how it can seamlessly connect a text-based experience to a strong, eerie visual presentation. The thick atmosphere and the pace at which the cryptic plot is explored are some of the strongest assets of the game. Everything worked to keep me on the edge of my seat throughout the better part of the experience. 

However, No Code didn't hit the nail in the head in every aspect with this one. As previously implied, you'll spend a significant amount of time wrestling around with enigmas and puzzles, some of which can become a bit tedious. In my opinion this is a small hindrance in the flow of the game as it managed to keep me immersed during most of the time. The only real major issue I have with Stories Untold is how the game has everything within its reach to get us, the players, fully commited and involved in the narrative, as to ultimately reward the player and avoiding dooming him/her to that one single ending, but ultimately chooses not to and doesn't even acknowledge it. I understand what a linear story is about, but the feeling that you're playing "against" a dumb AI should never be present at a game as linear as this ; you shouldn't be given room to think it. Allowing the player to actively take part in the game's narrative would've also given the game [i]some[/i] replay value, which it gravely lacks. Thus, No Code missed the mark in terms of ultimately delivering the ultimate psychological thriller.

All in all, [b]Stories Untold[/b] is a pretty good psychological visual novel. For those of you wondering, there's no actual horror in this game. The atmosphere is heavy and eerie and there's one or two scarier moments but it's not much, really. At the end of the day, Stories Untold feels like Her Story meets Gone Home... with a dash of Stranger Things minus most of the teenage drama. And I mean all of this in a good way.

7/10

35586366.review:
[h1] [b] Por que tu deveria jogar esse jogo? [/b] [/h1]

Pois é, o jogo pode até parecer difícil, porém é bastante gratificante quanto tu consegue passar de alguma fase [spoiler] SEM CHEATS NÉ GALERINHA [/spoiler] e pegar todos as conquistas. Além de rodar bastante bem num PC como o meu (se tu quiser pode ver na minha bio da Steam), ele tem gráficos bastante leves comparado aos outros games, e tenho certeza que ele roda em [b] QUASE [/b] qualquer PC.

O jogo se passa nos anos 80, relembrando realmente e dando um toque de ''oldskool'' nas coisas que ele apresenta, como nos computadores/máquinas, sons e derivados.

Vamos aos pontos positivos e negativos.

[h1] [b] Pontos Positivos [/b] [/h1]
[list]
[*] Gráficos bons;
[*] Contém conquistas (até que bastante fáceis de platinar);
[*] Contém boas referências;
[*] História envolvente e interessante;
[*] Boa atmosfera;
[*] Você não vê o tempo passar enquanto joga;
[*] Consegue agregar uma atmosfera bem agressiva quando é necessário;
[*] Boa jogabilidade;
[*] Point And Click, puzzle e te ajuda no seu vocabulário em inglês/língua estrangeira;
[*] O jogo consegue te acalmar em certos momentos.
[/list]

[h1] [b] Pontos Negativos [/b] [/h1]
[list]
[*] Não tem tradução para português;
[*] Precisa saber razoavelmente falar em inglês;
[*] Um pouco curto;
[*] Não há cartinhas :(;
[*] Acaba com a energia da sua casa quando você mais precisa dela;
[*] GET OUT GET OUT GET OUT THE CAR GET OU GET OUT GET OUT THE CAR
[*] Contém alguns erros de escrita;
[*] Você seguir um caminho ''trilhado'', não há como pular, por exemplo;
[*] [spoiler] Você precisará saber código Morse, infelizmente (emoji brabo) [/spoiler]
[*] [spoiler] It's all YOUR fault. [/spoiler]
[/list]

[h1] [b] Dicas: [/b] [/h1]
[list]
[*] Às vezes você clica e arrasta com o mouse;
[*] Às vezes você dígita, diferenciando maíusculo e minúsculo, em um computador;
[*] Às vezes você aperta TAB para se mover ao redor da tua mesa;
[*] Às vezes você aperta outras teclas;
[*] [spoiler] ALWAYS LOOK AROUND. [/spoiler]
[/list]

Na minha opinião, o jogo foi fantástico, não tão fácil, e bem criativo. Ele me impressionou de várias formas, tanto no enredo quanto na jogabilidade.

[h1] [b] Nota final: [/b] [/h1]
[b] 9/10. [/b]
